お好み ♥︎ Okonomi-Lovers

Welcome to this little Introduction to the best dish in the world: Okonomiyaki. You may have not heard of it (yet) and you might find it very rarely outside of Japan, thanks to their biggest food import Sushi. But after scrolling through this page, you will find yourself with a strange craving for Okonomiyaki!

Okonomiyaki, written like this: お好み焼き, is a savoury pancake-like dish with a lot of different flavours. Some people also call it the "Japanese pizza".
The name stems from the words okonomi お好み, meaning choice or preference and yaki 焼き, to fry or heat something. Okonomiyaki means "have it as you like" and that is the golden rule of this dish. You can add as many or as little toppings as you like. There is no right or wrong. You can have a completely different meal every time. Let's have a look at the most popular versions.

Okonomiyaki Osaka Style

The Kansai or better known as Osaka style is the most famous version of Okonomiyaki, especially outside of Japan. It's made of the basic ingredients flour, naigamo, dashi, cabbage and egg, that are all mixed together and fried on a teppan/hot plate. The basic version is topped with pork belly, but a lot of people enjoy it with squid, shrimp, cheese or several vegetables. The best thing (at least for me) are the sauces. Depending on the flavours of your toppings, japanese mayonaise (which is different from the one you know) and okonomi sauce is used to give it its signiture flavour. Years ago, only Worchester sauce has been used and is now the base of the okonomi sauce, which also includes ketchup. It's definitely super tasty! You finish it with aonori (grinded sea weed) and Bonito flakes. Bonito adds some umami taste, but are not for the faint of heart, if you don't like the taste of fish. Due to their fineness they appear to be "dancing" from the hot steam.

  • Flour
  • Naigamo
  • Dashi (made with water)
  • Cabbage
  • Eggs
  • Tenkasu
  • Pork belly or topping of your choice
  • Green Onions
  • Aonori
  • Bonito-Flakes
  • Japanse Mayonaise
  • Okonomi Sauce
  • optional: pickled ginger

Wisk the flour, grated naigamo (it becomes quite sticky!) and dashi until you have a smooth texture. Put it in the fridge for 1 hour. Meanwhile cut the cabbage and the green onions into small slices. Then mix the batter with the cabbage und the eggs (and pickled ginger if you like to).
Use a pan or your teppan grill and fry your batter for 5 minutes. Put the pork belly or the topping of your choice on top and flip the whole thing. Fry for 5 minutes then flip again. When it has a gloden brown colour, you can serve it on a plate, topped with the sauces, aonori und bonito.

Okonomiyaki Hiroshima Style

Another famous Okonomiyaki style originated in Hiroshima. You will hardly find it outside of Japan (that is the experience I made). The ingredients are basically the same, but Yakisoba (friend noodles) are added to the basic version. That makes it very hearty and filling. And instead of the cabbage and the eggs mixed with the batter, the Okonomiyaki is made in layers, which adds a very different flavour, as the taste of the eggs are much more prominent. It's also served with Mayonaise and Okonomi-sauce.
Making Hiroshima style Okonomiyaki is not for beginners and can be very frustrating, as you need to flip all the layers several times and you need to try to spill as little as possible. :) But it's worth a try.

  • Flour
  • Naigamo
  • Dashi (made with water)
  • Cabbage
  • Eggs
  • Tenkasu
  • Yakisoba Noodles
  • Bacon or topping of your choice
  • Green Onions
  • Aonori
  • Grinded Bonito-Flakes
  • Japanse Mayonaise
  • Okonomi Sauce
  • optional: pickled ginger

Wisk the flour, grated Naigamo (it becomes quite sticky!) and Dashi until you have a smooth texture. Put it in the fridge for 1 hour. Meanwhile cut the cabbage and the green onions into small slices. Cook the noodles according to the instructions.
Use a pan or your teppan grill and fry your batter (it should look like a crepe). Immediately put the Bonito, the cabbage and bacon or the toppings of your choice in layers on the batter and use a scoop of the batter on top before you flip the whole thing. When your "toppings" are fried, put the okonomiyaki aside.
Stir fry your noodles with a little oil and okonomi sauce. When done, make the noodles into a round shape, as you top it with your okonomiyaki now.
Fry an egg into the same shape as the okonomiyaki and place th okonomiyaki on it. Then flip the whole thing. The egg should now be the top layer with the noodles as the second.
Serve it on a plate with greens onions, pickled ginger, Aonori, Mayonaise and Sauces.

Other Okonomiyaki-like dishes

If you thought, this were all the okonomi dishes around - think again. Japan is full of different varieties of the famous dish. Some are made with pickled radish, some with beans or chicken. Just as you like it. Some very different versions are shown below.

Monjayaki

Monjayaki is kind of the Tokyo-style version of Okonomiyaki. The ingredients are similar, but more dashi and water is added, making it very mushy. You eat it directly from the hot plate with little spatulas.

Hirayachi

The Okinawa-originated dish is quite a simple distinguishable version of Okonomiyaki and usually cooked at home. It's made of flour, eggs, salt, pepper and green onions topped with Worchester sauce.

Fuchuyaki

Named after its place of origin, Fuchu, this Okonomiyaki-like dish is made with ground meat. It's more similar to the Hiroshima version.

Kakioko

Kakioko is a regional dish in Hinase, Okayama, and uses Oysters as its main ingredient. As oysters are the most important industry in this town, a lot of tourists flock in for this meal.

How to make Okonomiyaki yourself

You can easily make Okonomiyaki at home. The recipes are available above and you don't need a high-end japanese restaurant kitchen. If you have a teppan grill, that's good, but a simple pan will also help and get you some nice round okonomiyaki. The more exotic ingredients, like Dashi or Nagaimo, are usually available in Asia supermarkets.
